    "review": [
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "tonye"
            },
            "reviewBody": "This is as simple as it can get.\n\nA simpler way to make it ( as in Pans & Co ) is to puree the tomato, garlic, salt and olive oil in a food processor. We even cheat and use canned tomatoes ( I know, I know but right now tomatoes are not good, it's winter ). Toast the bread in the oven and use a brush to coat them with the tomaquet.\n\nSlice some cheeses, jamon serrano ( I buy a large deboned piece, softer than Iberico, and slice it with my own slicer ), chorizos ( blanco, cantimpalo, de Soria, etc..), fuet, lomo... \n\nAnchovies, a can of pulpos (or if you got it, some Pulpo de Soria).\n\nMake a salad.\n\nReserve some of the bread for the sobrasada, in the oven.\n\nHey! That's our dinner tonight.\n\nYou can come down, but it will cost you some good wine. ;-)"
        },
        {
            "@type": "Review",
            "author": {
                "@type": "Person",
                "name": "Ashley Povelaitis"
            },
            "reviewBody": "Can we leave out cheeses and the like? Save this. It is good almost how my grandma makes."
        }
    ],
